land":"St Briavels, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dene","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  See  Dean  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dahn","meanings":["German:","habitational name from a place in the Palatinate called Dahn.","(<b>Dähn</b>): ethnic name for a Dane, from Old Norse <i>Dan-</i>."]},{"name":"Dean","meanings":["English: topographic name from Middle English <i>dene</i> ‘valley’ (Old English <i>denu</i>), or a habitational name from any of several places in various parts of England named Dean or Dene from this word.","English: nickname or occupational name for the servant of a dean or nickname for someone thought to resemble a dean. A dean was an ecclesiastical official, the head of a chapter of canons or a church official with jurisdiction over a sub-division of an archdeaconry. Though no doubt some deans had illegitimate children, they were officially celibate, and in the main the surname is probably a nickname in origin, similar to   Bishop  ,   Prior  ,   Priest  , and   Monk  . The Middle English word <i>deen</i>, <i>dien</i>, <i>dein</i>, is a borrowing of Old French <i>d(e)ien</i>, <i>doien</i> from Latin <i>decanus</i> (originally a leader of ten men, from <i>decem</i> ‘ten’), and thus is a cognate of   Deacon  .","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Deyne</i> (or <i>Dene</i>) a rhyming pet form of <i>Reynald</i> (see   Reginald  )."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Dene Knight was born in 1266, in St Briavels, Glo